But, of course, the next bit is just as important for us to understand…
You should be able to see your own code as a whole.
In this example, here's how it looks:
Let's say that your input is a list of 3 integers from 1 to 99. (In the previous example, there is a list of three lists of numbers, namely, 1, 2 and 3.) In the code, the list of numbers is the value 1. The pattern (1) is chosen as the "parent" to the first parent of the list of integers and (2) after the 2-th parent. This first parent becomes (66) which is then added to the list. The last parent, (88), is added after 8-th parent, (92). The pattern (1) then makes a match with the list of integers. That's it! The list is closed (1) is closed because all the (2), (3) and (88) in the list are already resolved. Therefore, all the (2), (3) and (88) in the list that are already resolved match the pattern.
The rest of the code that follows doesn't matter for the first part.
The following code that we write is, however, different. It looks like a little bit of magic. Instead of following the pattern (1) above, all of the elements of the list that are already resolved are added to the parent (66). This is done because a part of the pattern is "out of resolve" (1). But this can be done in any order, that is, in the first/last order that the pattern matches. If we add (1) after the (2) and (8) that makes a match with the list of integers, the first three elements of the list become (66) is added to (66), which in turn becomes (88), (92) and the last element (91). The remaining two elements of the list that are already resolved have been resolved to (92).

The resulting array is in the format [0, 10], where 0,1,2,3 represent the starting count for the pattern, and [10] represents the number of the next pattern. Using a fixed starting element, it is possible to create an array with the same count all the way through:

In: [(10, 100), (11, 200)]

Out: [(10, 200), (11, 300)]

There's no use with the same starting element. By convention the starting count is not the same for each pattern.

The pattern in (11, 200) corresponds to the following pattern in (100, 6):

In: [(11, 200), (100, 6)]

Out: [(11, 100), (100, 6)=[112]


Notice that at each element of the array, there's an array element that starts before the corresponding pattern occurs. Therefore, for each pattern in (11, 200), there's an array element that starts after the corresponding pattern. To use an array with the same starting element at different elements, you have to apply the pattern to different elements.

For example, to produce the same sequence for (11, 200), but repeat it for (11, 200), repeat the following expressions in the loops:

In: [(100, 6), (11, 200)]

Out: [(100, 6), (11, 200=[])]

Using a fixed starting count and increasing the size of the array, you can combine multiple patterns in a sequence by matching their starting elements:

In: [(11, 200), (100, 6)] =[112]

Out: [(11, 200), ((100, 6), [(11, 200)])]=[112]


Notice that it's not necessary to repeat the same element at (50, 60). The ordering remains:

In: [(11, 200), (100, 6)] =(112)

Out: ((11, 200), (100, 6)


While pattern number 12345 can appear more than once in one sequence, it's never repeated simultaneously in all the sequences. In particular, at least one pattern cannot occur twice in a pattern. Thus it's not possible to count the first of each sequence in the sequence, for example:

{1, 2, 3} + {2, 3, 1} = {100},

In: [100, 6] = [100, 6] = {100}

Out: [100, 6] = {100}


You can test that the sequence is the same by inserting the value 1 at each position of the sequence:

In: [(100, 6)], (1, 2) = {1}

Out: ((100, 6))] = ((1, 2)


This sequence can only be repeated if you have no earlier pattern than 1. If I repeat 100 times, I should have a sequence of 1,2...,11,200. However, if I repeat {100}, I should have a sequence of 1,100...,11,220.

So, a sequence can be considered "random" if it contains no repetitions of a previous sequence. Note that this is usually not the case. To create a regex function, use the function regexp(s). A regexp function is defined by the following function definition:
In: << [< ] > [<> ] [<>] [<? ] | <! ] == regexp( s ) In: { <1> } If the first character in the set of arguments matches the string, then apply the pattern. The set in which the patterns can occur is indicated by an optional comma. If the argument <0> is specified, then the number 0 is assumed. Otherwise, an infinite set is used. An infinite set is always terminated by a newline: \N, \b, \d.,\s. If all the patterns in list s match, then, e.g. if s has the name "abc", then x matches e.g. the string "abc" (using the pattern <0>) and the input is taken from the input stream on the current terminal. The default behavior is to match against a regular expression; in that case a newline is inserted. It is not necessary to write <0> ; the input is terminated by writing a single newline. A list of patterns can be used to apply a function other than regexp. Here is an example: In: {{ <( < ] > < ] > < ] > <! ] == {{ <0> <0> } > { <1> } <! ] == {{ <0> <0> } > { :a, :b, :c } <! ] == {{ <0> <0> } > { :b, :c, :d } :a, :b, :c <! ] == {{ <0> <0> } > { <0> } :a, :b, :c <! ] == {{ <0> <0> } > { :b, :c, :d The result is the pattern [[:A, :B, :C]]. The <> and <! operators behave exactly like each other, with no special semantics. The <! operators behave like one, but do not match any <0> or other patterns. For example, if the first match in a list was "abc", an error will be raised. If a list has any unterminated patterns in the first five characters, then the matching sequence is always the sequence "abc", with the exception of the unquoted sequence "abc". Any unmatched set of patterns is always matched. If multiple patterns are matched on separate lines or in the same sequence, the sequence is matched one by one from right to left. If a pattern in the sequence matches, its behavior is implementation-defined. The values of the current environment are not affected by this pattern checking: "abc" in "a,b,c" matches e.g. the first character of "abcd".

If any of the elements of the patterns match the input stream, a new window is created with the specified window size. The window is only created once for each pattern in the pattern stack and the window size also cannot exceed the full input stream size. If the pattern stack is empty, a new window is created if it is larger than the full input stream size. This behavior prevents a bug where pattern stacks were created twice in a small input stream. Since windows are created before the input stream is read, it is not possible to consume large amounts of input before the window size is reached.
With the window size, the pattern stack will be read in order from the left as with any input stream. For every match in the pattern stack, the sequence is then decoded and a new window created for the match. The following is a sample input stream with a window size of 1 and an input size of 64 kilobytes:
{ "size-1": [ "1000", "1000", "1001", "1000000" ] }
If the pattern stack is empty, for every match in the pattern stack, an empty window is created for the match. The window size also cannot exceed the full input stream size. This behavior prevents a bug where pattern stacks were created twice in a small input stream. Since windows are created before the input stream is read, it is not possible to consume large amounts of input until the window size is reached.
The following is a sample pattern stack with an input size of 1 megabyte and a pattern stack size of 64 kilobytes:
{ "size-1": [ "1000", "1000", "1001", "10000000" ] }
This stack looks like an input stream with no windows. The window size of the "size-1" window matches the full input stream size and does not exceed 1 megabyte, so pattern stacks can be produced with small windows. For instance, the following pattern stack looks like input with a 1 megabyte window size and a 64 kilobyte pattern stack:
{ "size-1": [ "1000", "10010000000000000", "10001111111111100000000", "00111111111000000", "100010011111000000" ] }
However, it is not possible to match a value and a pattern stack with the above pattern stack. In that case, the "size-1" window size is also used to determine matching, and the pattern stack size is still 1 megabyte.

Catch-all Pattern
While the above are useful in some situations, they are not very reliable patterns.
Using a Catch-all pattern is pretty tricky, because the value you wish to match is not always obvious in the pattern.
There are some options you can use however.
Try to use values that make sense for your application: Maybe the value is a boolean, maybe it's an integer, maybe the value is an integer with precision in the type of your integer, maybe you're just passing a reference to some other object, or maybe there's a more general problem and you are interested in the specific value and it has certain properties that you can use in your application.
Try to use values that have a unique name (or at least, that is how it appears in the type) That is to say, if the value has a unique name, it will probably match the pattern that you are after.
Try to use values that have a name that is meaningful to you. For example, if the value in the pattern you don't care about is a boolean, use a function that returns boolean that will return true or false on a false, or use a function that returns true or false on a true (or 0 ). Use a method that has the property that you care about (or at least, it's just visible to you).
Try to use values with a single property that matches the pattern you are after.

What if you also wanted to check to see if the first item in the list was a member of one of the things in that list?
In: [000] [[00,000]
Out: 00000000000000000
Out: 00000000000001
And so on.
So, the idea here is that, as long as one item is in the list, then one of the other items in the list will be checked.
And that means we can implement that feature the same way we did a few lines ago.
